summary.value:
The current COVID-19 pandemic is a common source of stress and governmental measures are disrupting daily life in almost every country. This situation is a clear “experiment of nature” that could allow stress researchers to understand the psychological aspects of experiencing a pandemic in the 21st century.
Contrary to other crises, social isolation and radical changes in the way individuals go about their daily lives are at the center of the current pandemic. Studying the psychosocial aspects of this crisis can help the population make sense of the challenges they are going through and to be better prepared, should a   similar crisis occur in the future. Given the potential length of this crisis, it’s probable recurrence in the months/years to come and lasting repercussions it may have on society, stress scientists can help anticipate negative repercussions and foster positive adaptations in the population.
A few already existing projects are now facing major barriers as a result of the pandemic, which may impede the proper completion of these projects. As such, the Center for Studies on Human Stress (CSHS) has decided to modify the nature of these projects. Given that:
-	The initial aim of this project was to evaluate the transition from university studies to the workplace;
-	Current graduates will not be representative of those of other years;
-	Biological sample collection and in-person meetings part of “non-essential” research projects have come to a halt at the Centre de Recherche de l’Institut Universitaire en Santé Mentale de Montréal;
-	We currently have 39 participants that were enrolled and active in the study before the onset of the crisis.
The CSHS decided to modify the main objective of the project to study psychological and social aspects of the COVID-19 crisis. The initial project was titled Brain Health for Economic Health (2019-1745) and was initially approved by the Institut Universitaire en Santé Mentale de Montréal’s research ethics committee on April 25th, 2019.
We are contacting previous participants in the project with a selected series of questionnaires from the initial study along with a questionnaire specific to the crisis, developed by the CSHS and collaborators. The first data collection (that has already been collected) will be used as a “pre-crisis” measurement and current responses will be compared to this baseline. 
Responses to the questionnaire will be matched with information that is relevant to the pandemic on the day that the response was completed. This will be done to account for variability that may be due to objective changes in the severity of the crisis. Furthermore, no biological samples will be collected during this study.

